@node INTRO "Tickle92.guide/Introduction"
@next REQUIREMENTS
@prev MAIN

                               @{b}@{u}INTRODUCTION@{uu}@{ub}


Tickle92 is a linking environment for Texas Instruments' TI-92 calculator.
It is used send and receive variables to and from the TI. You can also
send and receive backups, and receive a ROM dump.

There are also some additional goodies; CaptROM - the ROM dump program
already mentioned, and Remote92 - a utility to remote-control your TI-92
with. Plus a last-minute one; FLink, which is a Fargo linker.

There is a wide variety of software available for the TI-92. Perhaps most
interestingly, a wide selection of games that run under the ZShell
environment. The following address is a very good starting point for
finding TI-92 software:

    http://www.ticalc.org/

The linking cable used is the parallel link cable that is used by some PC
and Mac software also. The reasons to use a parallel cable are many; it's
cheap, it's easy to make, it doesn't occupy the serial port, and there is
already linking software that uses the serial port, namely ALink.

Tickle is shell based, you use two simple commands to send and receive
variables from the TI-92. Namely @{" Send92 " link U_SEND} and @{" Recv92 " link U_RECV}.

That's what you get, hope you enjoy it.

@endnode
@node REQUIREMENTS "Tickle92.guide/Requirements"
@next INSTALLATION
@prev INTRO

                               @{b}@{u}REQUIREMENTS@{uu}@{ub}


Tickle requires AmigaOS 2.0, not that the program does anything the 1.3 OS
can't do, but some DOS functions were too primitive in 1.3.

Also, you need a parallel-link cable, building instructions are included.

@endnode
@node INSTALLATION "Tickle92.guide/Installation"
@next CABLE
@prev REQUIREMENTS

                               @{b}@{u}INSTALLATION@{uu}@{ub}


The software can be run as it is, but the installer allows you to set up
paths and such. Before you can link with a TI-92 though, you need to build
yourself a link cable following the instructions that came with Tickle. The
cable is exactly the same as the parallel cable that is used on PCs.

Once the cable is built, you can check its functionality with the
TICableTest program, or you can simply try transferring some files.

@endnode
@node CABLE "Tickle85.guide/Cable"
@prev INSTALLATION
@next U_SEND

                                 @{b}@{u}THE CABLE@{uu}@{ub}

Tickle uses the parallel-port linking cable designed by Andreas Westfeld.
It is the same cable as the one used on the PC. Building instructions are
included in the archive, it's a slightly modified copy of Andreas
Westfeld's instructions, that can be found at:

    http://www.ticalc.org/mirror/parallel/index.html

Anyway, you need a web-browser to read the instructions, they are in the
TICable subdirectory, if you installed using the installer.

If you have some sort of HTML-datatype, you can go to the
@{" cable building instructions " link TICable/index.html/main} directly.

@endnode
@node U_SEND
@next U_RECV
@prev CABLE

                                  @{b}@{u}SEND92@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Template:@{ub} FILE/A,FOLDER,FORCE/S:

Send92 is used to send files to the TI-92. To send a variable to the 
TI, simply make sure that your TI-92 is on the home screen and not 
busy (i.e. make sure you aren't doing anything with it). Then start 
Send92 with the desired arguments.

@{b}INPUTS@{ub}

    FILE -- File which should be uploaded to the TI-92.

    FOLDER -- Folder in which to place files that don't have a folder
    specified internally. (optional)

    FORCE -- Forces Send92 to place all the variables in the specified
    folder. (optional)

For further information on variable transmissions, consult you 
TI-92's manual.

@endnode
@node U_RECV
@next U_CAPTROM
@prev U_SEND

                                  @{b}@{u}RECV92@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Template:@{ub} FILE/A,REQUEST/M,FOLDER=DEFAULTFOLDER/K,COMMENT/K,BACKUP/S,
          BUF=BACKUPBUF/N

Recv92 is used to receive files from the TI-92. To receive variables, 
you can either request variables, or you can select the variables on 
the TI. To request variables simply start Recv92 with the filename 
and the variables as arguments. If you do not want to request 
variables, you start Recv92 with the filename only, then start the 
send on your TI-92.

@{i}Note on receiving backups: @{ui}If you receive backups bigger than 128kilobytes,
you must specify a larger backupbuffer using the BACKUPBUF argument.

@{b}INPUTS@{ub}

    FILE -- File into which the variables will be saved.

    REQUEST -- Request variables from the TI, multiple variables possible.
    (optional)

    DEFAULTFOLDER -- A folder name which will be placed in the file header.
    When sending back to the TI-92, variables which don't have a folder
    specified will be placed in this folder. (optional)

    COMMENT -- Comment to place in the comment section of the variable.
    (optional)

    BACKUP -- Requests backup of TI's memory. (optional)

    BACKUPBUF -- The buffersize into which the backup is stored, this must
    be bigger or at least as big as the backup received. By default it is
    set to 128kbytes. This argument is not used normally, but may be 
    required if you have more than the original TI-92's amount of 
    memory

For further information on variable transmission consult your TI-92's 
manual. 

@endnode
@node U_CAPTROM
@next U_REMOTE
@prev U_RECV

                                 @{b}@{u}CAPTROM92@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Template:@{ub} Captrom <filename>

Captrom enables you to download the ROM of your TI-92 into a file.

There are few reasons to grab the ROM from your TI-92, you do not need to
have it on your computer for any general purposes. However, you may want to
peek into it, use it in a TI-92 emulator (if there will be one), or you may
just want to have it. Whatever your reasons may be, feel content that you
can grab the ROM.

To grab a ROM, start captrom with the filename to store the ROM in, then
start one of the ROM-sending programs that is distributed with Fargo, the
one that sends in binary form, whichever that is...

@endnode
@node U_REMOTE "Tickle92.guide/Usage/Remote92"
@next U_CABLETEST
@prev U_CAPTROM

                                 @{b}@{u}REMOTE92@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Template:@{ub} NOLACE/S

Remote92 allows you to remote control your TI-92 using your Amiga. You are
presented with a view of your TI-92 in a small window, and you can type in
commands into it just as you would normally on your TI-92.

The internals of the remote control program do not use the TI-92's built-in
remote-control features, it work so that it sends the input to the TI-92
and requests a screen-dump from the TI-92 afterwards. This makes it
unfortunately slow, but is mostly meant as a toy.

Shifted characters and some other special characters are not (yet)
supported.

@{i}Note: @{ui}If you type too fast the TI may send you a screen-dump too early, and
won't display the result of the latest input on the screen. If this is the
case, press F10 and the screen will be updated.

@{b}INPUTS@{ub}

    NOLACE -- Makes the display look good on non-proportional screens.

@{b}SPECIAL KEYS@{ub}

    There are a few keys on the TI that don't exist on the Amiga, Amiga
    equivalents are as follows:

        TI-92 key | <Amiga key>
        ==========|============
         Apps     | TAB
         Mode     | Help
         ESC      | ` (to the left of `1')
         Clear    | DEL
         ln       | ĺ or [ (to the right of `P')
         ^        | ¨ or ] (to the right of the previous)
         sin      | ö or ; (to the right of `L')
         cos      | ä or ´ (to the right of the previous)
         tan      | ' (to the right of the previous)

@endnode
@node U_FLINK "Tickle92.guide/Usage/FLink"
@next U_CABLETEST
@prev U_REMOTE

                                   @{b}@{u}FLINK@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Template:@{ub} OBJFILE/A,TO,NAME,FOLDER,COMMENT:

FLink is a linker for Fargo programs. It links a '.o' file that has been
output from A68k into a TI-92 variable. If you know what I mean, you might 
have some use of this program, if you don't, you probably don't need it.

@{b}INPUTS@{ub}

    OBJFILE -- The object file that should be linked.

    TO -- Output file, if none is specified, it uses the OBJFILE, but
    appends '.92p' instead of '.o'. (optional)

    NAME -- The name of the variable, OBJFILE by default. (optional)

    FOLDER -- The name of the folder into which the variable should be
    placed. (optional)

    COMMENT -- The comment that is put into the variable-file.

@endnode
@node U_CABLETEST "Tickle92.guide/Usage/Cabletest"
@next LINKS
@prev U_REMOTE

                                @{b}@{u}TICABLETEST@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Template:@{ub} TICableTest

The cabletest program is used to see if your cable and/or parallel port
are okay. The test is performed in steps, during which the program sets
link-cable to different states. Your task is to check whether the
link-cable is in these steps, to do this you need a voltmeter of some
kind.

The output on the screen refers to the phono-plug, i.e. the plug that
connects into your TI-92. You are to measure the voltage between ground
(the root-part of the phono-plug) and the tip, and similarly between the
ground and the middle of the plug. Compare the readings to those reported
on the screen.

The voltage should read between 3 and 5 volts when it is HIGH, and near 0
volts when it is LOW.

@{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}

The output at first should look like this:

    > Init - both tip and mid HIGH

Now measure the voltage between the tip and the root (ground) of the phono
plug, it should read something between 3 and 5 volts. Now do the same
between the middle and the root of the plug. It should show approximately
the same voltage.

Now press return once, and the line

    > 0 - both LOW

should turn up. Do the measurings again - both should read 0 volts.

Continue in this manner, checking that the tip is high and low when it
should be, and that the mid is high and low when it should be. If all
readings are okay, your cable is fine, and any problems lie elsewhere.

@{b}TROUBLESHOOTING@{ub}

If your readings don't match the info on the screen, it's time to check the
results carefully. Here is a small checklist:

    o Check that you haven't short-cut any wires, you may recognize them as
      both pins being HIGH in step 1 or 2. If this is the case, look
      through your soldering for short-cuts.

    o Check that you haven't flipped the cables at any point, this will
      probably show up by the results in steps 1 and 2 being flipped. If
      this is the case, check you soldering and flip the cables.

    o Check that you don't have not got any broken connections, this will
      show as the one broken being constantly LOW. If this is the case,
      check your soldering for bad joints, and your cable.

    o Always double check your solderings.

@endnode
